<h2>High temperatures at the end of March</h2>
In the last days of March 2021, much of Europe was under high-pressure influence. Warm subtropical air flowed into western parts of the high-pressure area especially to Western and Central Europe. Combined with long sunshine duration, partly new local March records of maximum temperature were reached in large parts of Europe.
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/mar2021/Europe-weather-march-31-2021.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2021/Europe-weather-march-31-2021.jpg" width="350px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Weather analysis 2m temperature 31 March 2021 12:00 UTC (source: GFS)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Numerous records of highest March maximum temperature were broken this month, particularly on 31 March 2021, or at least very high temperatures exceeding 25-30&#176;C were reported for that day:
<br><br>
Spain: 32.4&#176;C at Badajoz Airport (southwest Spain);
<br><br>
France: 29.8&#176;C in Bidache (Pyrenees maritime);
<br><br>
Italy: 29.4&#176;C in Florence;
<br><br>
Germany: 27.2&#176;C in Rheinau-Memprechtshofen in the Upper Rhine Valley;
<br><br>
Slovenia: 25.3&#176;C in Ljubljana;
<br><br>
Czech Republic: 25.1&#176;C in Prague-Karlov;
<br><br>
Switzerland: 25.0&#176;C in Basel-Binningen.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for March 2021</h2>
<br><br>
Temperatures varied considerably over Europe during March 2021, but were not extreme on average over the continent. The month as a whole was milder than usual over north-western Europe, especially over Norway and Sweden. It was colder than the 1981-2010 reference period over south-eastern and far eastern Europe.
<br><br>
There is a sharp contrast in temperatures regime between the western and eastern half of Scandinavia which can be nicely seen in the minimum of daily minimum temperature in March 2021 and the anomaly w.r.t. 1981-201
<br><br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
